    Code 
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Create a figure with 2x2 subplots, sharing x and y axes
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=2, figsize=(10, 8), 
                         sharex=True, sharey=True)  # Share both x and y axes

# Generate some sample data
x = np.linspace(0, 10, 100)
y1 = np.sin(x)
y2 = np.cos(x)
y3 = np.sin(x) * np.exp(-0.1*x)
y4 = np.cos(x) * np.exp(-0.1*x)

# Plot data on each subplot and add text
axes[0, 0].plot(x, y1, 'r-')
axes[0, 0].text(5, 0, "Hello from ax 0,0", ha='center', fontsize=12, 
                bbox=dict(facecolor='white', alpha=0.8))

axes[0, 1].plot(x, y2, 'g-')
axes[0, 1].text(5, 0, "Hello from ax 0,1", ha='center', fontsize=12,
                bbox=dict(facecolor='white', alpha=0.8))

axes[1, 0].plot(x, y3, 'b-')
axes[1, 0].text(5, 0, "Hello from ax 1,0", ha='center', fontsize=12,
                bbox=dict(facecolor='white', alpha=0.8))

axes[1, 1].plot(x, y4, 'm-')
axes[1, 1].text(5, 0, "Hello from ax 1,1", ha='center', fontsize=12,
                bbox=dict(facecolor='white', alpha=0.8))

# Add titles to each subplot
axes[0, 0].set_title('Sine Wave')
axes[0, 1].set_title('Cosine Wave')
axes[1, 0].set_title('Damped Sine Wave')
axes[1, 1].set_title('Damped Cosine Wave')

# Add a main title for the entire figure
fig.suptitle('Example with 4 Subplots (sharex=True, sharey=True)', fontsize=16)

# Only the bottom subplots need x-labels (due to sharex=True)
axes[1, 0].set_xlabel('X-axis')
axes[1, 1].set_xlabel('X-axis')

# Only the left subplots need y-labels (due to sharey=True)
axes[0, 0].set_ylabel('Y-axis')
axes[1, 0].set_ylabel('Y-axis')

# Adjust spacing between subplots
plt.tight_layout()
plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.9)  # Make room for the suptitle

# Display the plot
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Monthly sales data (in thousands)
months = range(1, 13)
sales_2024 = [45, 48, 53, 58, 63, 68, 72, 74, 70, 65, 60, 55]

# Create a figure with 1 row and 3 columns
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=3, figsize=(9, 3))

# Plot 1: Scatter plot (left)
axes[0].scatter(months, sales_2024, color='blue', s=100, alpha=0.7)
axes[0].set_title('Monthly Sales - Scatter', fontsize=9)
axes[0].set_xlabel('Month', fontsize=9)
axes[0].set_ylabel('Sales (thousands $)', fontsize=9)
axes[0].grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
axes[0].set_xticks(months)

# Plot 2: Line plot (middle)
axes[1].plot(months, sales_2024, color='green', linewidth=2, marker='o')
axes[1].set_title('Monthly Sales - Line', fontsize=9)
axes[1].set_xlabel('Month', fontsize=9)
axes[1].set_ylabel('Sales (thousands $)', fontsize=9)
axes[1].grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
axes[1].set_xticks(months)

# Plot 3: Bar chart (right)
axes[2].bar(months, sales_2024, color='orange', alpha=0.7)
axes[2].set_title('Monthly Sales - Bar', fontsize=9)
axes[2].set_xlabel('Month', fontsize=9)
axes[2].set_ylabel('Sales (thousands $)', fontsize=9)
axes[2].grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7, axis='y')
axes[2].set_xticks(months)
axes[2].set_xticklabels(months, rotation=-45)

# Add a main title for the entire figure
fig.suptitle('Monthly Sales (2025) - Multiple Plot Types', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')

# Adjust layout
plt.tight_layout()
plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.85)  # Make room for the suptitle

# Display the plot
plt.show()

Week 10: Hypothesis Testing and Confidence Intervals

Key Concepts

  1. Descriptive Statistics and Data Distributions
    • Mean, median, mode, variance, standard deviation
    • Visualizing distributions with histograms and box plots
    • Understanding the normal distribution
  2. Hypothesis Testing Fundamentals
    • Null and alternative hypotheses
    • P-values and significance levels (typically 0.05)
    • Type I and Type II errors
  3. Types of T-Tests
    • One-Sample T-Test: Compares a sample mean to a known value
    • Two-Sample T-Test: Compares means of two independent groups
    • Paired T-Test: Compares related samples (e.g., before/after measurements)
  4. Correlation Analysis
    • Pearson correlation coefficient
    • Visualization using correlation matrices and heatmaps
    • Interpretation of positive, negative, and zero correlations
  5. Confidence Intervals
    • Interval estimation for population parameters
    • Interpretation of confidence levels (e.g., 95% confidence)
    • Applications in business decision-making

Example: One-Sample T-Test

Problem: A company wants to determine if its customer satisfaction rating is significantly different from a benchmark of 4.0. The ratings are collected from a sample of customers.

Code 
import numpy as np
from scipy import stats

# Sample customer satisfaction ratings (scale of 1 to 5)
ratings = np.array([4.2, 3.8, 4.0, 4.5, 3.9, 4.1, 4.3])
benchmark = 4.0

# Perform a one-sample t-test
t_stat, p_value = stats.ttest_1samp(ratings, benchmark)
print("One-Sample T-Test: Customer Satisfaction")
print("T-Statistic:", t_stat)
print("P-value:", p_value)

# Add interpretation of results
alpha = 0.05  # Total significance level for the two-tailed test
if p_value < alpha:
    print(f"Result: Reject the null hypothesis (p < {alpha}).")
    print("Interpretation: The mean customer satisfaction rating is significantly different from the benchmark value of 4.0.")
    
    # Determine direction of difference (only relevant if null is rejected)
    if np.mean(ratings) > benchmark:
        print("Specifically, the mean rating is significantly higher than the benchmark.")
    else:
        print("Specifically, the mean rating is significantly lower than the benchmark.")
else:
    print(f"Result: Fail to reject the null hypothesis (p >= {alpha}).")
    print("Interpretation: There is insufficient evidence to conclude that the mean customer satisfaction rating")
    print("                differs from the benchmark value of 4.0.")

# Additional descriptive statistics
print("\nDescriptive Statistics:")
print(f"Sample Mean: {np.mean(ratings):.2f}")
print(f"Sample Standard Deviation: {np.std(ratings, ddof=1):.2f}")

# Calculate the critical t-values for a two-tailed test
critical_t = stats.t.ppf([0.025, 0.975], len(ratings)-1)
print(f"Critical t-values (Î±/2 = 0.025 in each tail): {critical_t[0]:.3f} and {critical_t[1]:.3f}")

# Calculate and display confidence interval
confidence_level = 0.95
margin_of_error = stats.t.ppf((1 + confidence_level) / 2, len(ratings)-1) * (np.std(ratings, ddof=1)/np.sqrt(len(ratings)))
print(f"{int(confidence_level*100)}% Confidence Interval: ({np.mean(ratings) - margin_of_error:.2f}, {np.mean(ratings) + margin_of_error:.2f})")
One-Sample T-Test: Customer Satisfaction
T-Statistic: 1.2545000963743653
P-value: 0.2563154589158218
Result: Fail to reject the null hypothesis (p >= 0.05).
Interpretation: There is insufficient evidence to conclude that the mean customer satisfaction rating
                differs from the benchmark value of 4.0.

Descriptive Statistics:
Sample Mean: 4.11
Sample Standard Deviation: 0.24
Critical t-values (Î±/2 = 0.025 in each tail): -2.447 and 2.447
95% Confidence Interval: (3.89, 4.34)

NOTE: The null hypothesis (Hâ) for this test is:

âThe mean customer satisfaction rating is equal to 4.0.â

Mathematically, this would be expressed as: Hâ: Î¼ = 4.0

The alternative hypothesis (Hâ) would be:

âThe mean customer satisfaction rating is not equal to 4.0.â

Mathematically: Hâ: Î¼ â  4.0

This is a two-tailed test because weâre looking for any difference from the benchmark, whether higher or lower. The t-statistic and p-value from the test will tell us whether we have enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis:

  • If p-value < 0.05 (assuming a 5% significance level), we would reject the null hypothesis, indicating that the mean customer satisfaction rating is significantly different from 4.0.
  • If p-value â¥ 0.05, we would fail to reject the null hypothesis, suggesting there isnât enough evidence to conclude that the mean rating differs from 4.0.

The t-statistic tells us the size and direction of the difference between the sample mean and >the benchmark value, measured in standard error units.

## Week 10: Hypothesis Testing and Confidence Intervals

### Key Concepts

1. **Descriptive Statistics and Data Distributions**
   - Mean, median, mode, variance, standard deviation
   - Visualizing distributions with histograms and box plots
   - Understanding the normal distribution

2. **Hypothesis Testing Fundamentals**
   - Null and alternative hypotheses
   - P-values and significance levels (typically 0.05)
   - Type I and Type II errors

3. **Types of T-Tests**
   - **One-Sample T-Test**: Compares a sample mean to a known value
   - **Two-Sample T-Test**: Compares means of two independent groups
   - **Paired T-Test**: Compares related samples (e.g., before/after measurements)

4. **Correlation Analysis**
   - Pearson correlation coefficient
   - Visualization using correlation matrices and heatmaps
   - Interpretation of positive, negative, and zero correlations

5. **Confidence Intervals**
   - Interval estimation for population parameters
   - Interpretation of confidence levels (e.g., 95% confidence)
   - Applications in business decision-making

### Example: One-Sample T-Test

Problem: A company wants to determine if its customer satisfaction rating is significantly different from a benchmark of 4.0. The ratings are collected from a sample of customers.

```{python}
import numpy as np
from scipy import stats

# Sample customer satisfaction ratings (scale of 1 to 5)
ratings = np.array([4.2, 3.8, 4.0, 4.5, 3.9, 4.1, 4.3])
benchmark = 4.0

# Perform a one-sample t-test
t_stat, p_value = stats.ttest_1samp(ratings, benchmark)
print("One-Sample T-Test: Customer Satisfaction")
print("T-Statistic:", t_stat)
print("P-value:", p_value)

# Add interpretation of results
alpha = 0.05  # Total significance level for the two-tailed test
if p_value < alpha:
    print(f"Result: Reject the null hypothesis (p < {alpha}).")
    print("Interpretation: The mean customer satisfaction rating is significantly different from the benchmark value of 4.0.")
    
    # Determine direction of difference (only relevant if null is rejected)
    if np.mean(ratings) > benchmark:
        print("Specifically, the mean rating is significantly higher than the benchmark.")
    else:
        print("Specifically, the mean rating is significantly lower than the benchmark.")
else:
    print(f"Result: Fail to reject the null hypothesis (p >= {alpha}).")
    print("Interpretation: There is insufficient evidence to conclude that the mean customer satisfaction rating")
    print("                differs from the benchmark value of 4.0.")

# Additional descriptive statistics
print("\nDescriptive Statistics:")
print(f"Sample Mean: {np.mean(ratings):.2f}")
print(f"Sample Standard Deviation: {np.std(ratings, ddof=1):.2f}")

# Calculate the critical t-values for a two-tailed test
critical_t = stats.t.ppf([0.025, 0.975], len(ratings)-1)
print(f"Critical t-values (Î±/2 = 0.025 in each tail): {critical_t[0]:.3f} and {critical_t[1]:.3f}")

# Calculate and display confidence interval
confidence_level = 0.95
margin_of_error = stats.t.ppf((1 + confidence_level) / 2, len(ratings)-1) * (np.std(ratings, ddof=1)/np.sqrt(len(ratings)))
print(f"{int(confidence_level*100)}% Confidence Interval: ({np.mean(ratings) - margin_of_error:.2f}, {np.mean(ratings) + margin_of_error:.2f})")
```

>NOTE: 
>The null hypothesis (Hâ) for this test is:
>
>"The mean customer satisfaction rating is equal to 4.0."
>
>Mathematically, this would be expressed as: Hâ: Î¼ = 4.0
>
>The alternative hypothesis (Hâ) would be:
>
>"The mean customer satisfaction rating is not equal to 4.0."
>
>Mathematically: Hâ: Î¼ â  4.0
>
>This is a two-tailed test because we're looking for any difference from the benchmark, 
 whether higher or lower. The t-statistic and p-value from the test will tell us whether we
 have enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis:
>
> * If p-value < 0.05 (assuming a 5% significance level), we would reject the null hypothesis, indicating that the mean customer satisfaction rating is significantly different from 4.0.
> * If p-value â¥ 0.05, we would fail to reject the null hypothesis, suggesting there isn't enough evidence to conclude that the mean rating differs from 4.0.
>
>The t-statistic tells us the size and direction of the difference between the sample mean and >the benchmark value, measured in standard error units.
